title: For Sale:  Ruger No. 1H Tropical .458 Win. Mag.
postcontent:
FOR SALE


Ruger No. 1H Tropical .458 Win. Mag.

This is the older variant of No. 1 with the red recoil pad and the single line of text on the top of the barrel. The rifle is in amazing shape, the pictures do little to convey the figure in the wood and the beautiful bluing. While the .458 Win. Mag. is eclipsed by a handful of more powerful cartridges and only hurls its 510gr bullets around 2000fps, this remains a substantial round in one of the most stout guns ever built, this rifle is a striking example of a fine old Ruger Tropical rifle.

This particular rifle was purchased used in the mid 1990s and has taken its share of large rocks and water jugs over the years. It has spent most of the last decade living in the dark corner of the safe and has not been fired in several years. As time passes my shoulder will tense at the thought of taking it out again and the slight recoil generated by its enormous power; the time may have come for the gun to go to a younger, less frail owner. Serial Number is: 130-16xxx

There is no box or paperwork, just the beast itself along with three factory loaded rounds (turning green as it has been so long since its been fired) and five pieces of once fired brass.

location: Lake in the Hills or Sycamore, IL, Chicago, Illinois
postcontent:
Reluctant to sell this upper but I've bought another upper for a KISS build.

Upper is a Del-Ton 16" M4 that I bought new, 1x9 and Chrome-lined. I installed a Troy lo-pro gas block, Magpul MOE handguard in Foliage green and just installed a brand-new Armalite clamp-on FSB. I have a Battlecomp 1.0 muzzle brake out front, does everything it was advertised to.  The upper has t-marks.  Included is a small section of rail on the port side.  All pics taken on 04/03 and are accurate.

Includes Del-ton charging handle and BCG, with BCM extractor upgrade kit.  Ejection port cover is laser etched and reads "Break Yo'Self", kind of subdued but I thought it was fun. Some edge wear on the FWD assist and some marks on the barrel, edge of the Battlecomp, etc. Nothing major nor concerning.

BCG is a semi-auto style carrier.  I bought the upper from Del-Ton about 3-4 months before they started MP testing their bolts so it is not MP tested nor has any marks.  The extractor has BCM's "donut" and spring with insert, and it flings brass with authority.  I've never had a single failure with this upper.  I have shot Tula/Wolf no problems, typically I shoot Winchester brass cased .223 from my local Farm'n'Fleet.  Total round count is no more than 12-1300.  Cleaned and oiled after every use.



I would sell the upper alone for $540 shipped and insured.  I accept discreet Paypal plus fees or as a GIFT.  Knock off $20 if you pickup with cash in person.  I have excellent feedback on AR15.com and E-Bay, etc. 

-add the MBUS Gen2 in Foliage for $45 (its new but no box, Genuine and not PTS)
-add a Vortex SPARC red dot with mount in 9.5/10 condition (including all factory stuff and screw-in 2x magnifier) for $170.

The upper includes a set of faux-Larue index clips (I rec'd in trade a while back ) that I used to cover the sections of rail unused.

Introducing AR MR2. This is a replacement to your current magazine lock or factory magazine catch we've developed  to address the latest round of bans in NY, MD, CT, and CA. It installs in about 5 minutes. 

AR MR2 is made from 7075-T6 Aluminum anodized to Military Specifications. All materials are made with pride in the USA, by local manufacturers!


This kit comes with complete installation instructions, and the work can be done by even the most novice of firearm owners

AR MR2 creates a fixed magazine rifle or pistol that requires disassembly of the AR firearm action to release the magazine. While the firearm is assembled, the magazine is fixed in place

Avoid costly registration, eventual confiscation, or prison by installing AR MR2. With AR MR2, you have a choice

A Blocking Washer is included with every kit shipped to create a top-load only configuration if desired

Note: They have been taping the washers down inside of every package next to the illustrated parts breakdown. This was a small part that worked its way out of the earlier orders (~6 months ago), and we’ve since remedied this issue on the assembly line

Legal Disclaimers:

If your state requires it, AR MR2 can be made permanent by epoxying the allen screw, and removing the allen facets with a 1/8" drill bit. The screw will be destroyed upon removal (we can ship you another one) meeting the permanence requirements set in some states. The receiver will not be capable of retaining ANY magazine until a replacement part is installed

title: For Sale/Trade:  Beautiful! - Beretta Brigadier Elite 2 - .40 S&W
postcontent:
Here for your consideration is a Beretta 96 / Brigadier Elite ll. This is a wonder to shoot. The gun is in great shape other than minimal wear mark from being shot. The gun has has about 200 rounds down the pipe, cleaned, and put into the safe. The Elite ll comes with two ten round magazines with rubber bumpers allowing them to drop free safely onto concrete. I will also include a leather OWB slide holster. The only thing missing is the orignal box. I recently moved to new house and cannot find it. New boxes can be had from Beretta for about 15$.

These are no longer manufactured and are very hard to come by. They have sold for as much as 1550.00 on gunbroker. This option replaced the Elite I option in 2001 and includes the same features as the original Elite plus removable Novak type sights, extended magazine release catch, checkered front/rear grip strap, thicker (than Elite I) skeletonized hammer, and lighter D-spring. This option is available only with the stainless G-Model slide, also with front serrations. The stainless barrel for the Elite II has a target crown. The elite ll has hogue wrap-around grips installed.

The thicker slide makes shooting the .40 S&W much lighter and allows for faster follow up shots. All factory accesories for the Beretta 96 will work if anything needs replaced in the future. The gun is sale as well as trade. Trying to see what is out there these days. I am interested in lots of things EXCEPT, single- action revolvers, bows, and electronics. I prefer Sigs, 1911's, H&K, and have always had my eye on a KelTec KSG. I will consider just about anything, but don't offer me an LCP and ask for a straight trade. If bling is your thing, this probably won't warm you up very much.  The chambers will accept up to 3 1/2" shells, but it has only seen 2 3/4" to date.  The barrels are Invector Plus choked.

It can be easily converted from shell ejection to shell extraction, which is how I used it.  The ejectors thus have very little mileage on them.  I also used it with extended chokes so the barrel ends have been well protected.

The gun is available for sale and inspection at Gilcrest Farm Supply, John Taylor proprietor.

title: For Sale:  COLT .357 MAGNUM
postcontent:
This is a very clean .357 Magnum Ctg. in excellent condition.  This .357 is built on the same frame as the Python and Lawman.  Blueing is 98+% with only slight thinning on the tip of the barrel sides and minor handling marks.  The barrel is 4in. with a shiny bore and strong rifling.  No flame cutting on the top strap above the cone.  Stocks look almost new. 
Lock-up is solid and action crisp with amazing single-action that is short and light. 
Nice Don Hume black leather holster included.
More pictures available to email.

Trooper: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colt_Trooper
1953 - 1969 The original Trooper was basically a heavy-barreled version of the Officers Model Match, and was based on Colt’s medium .41 frame. It was offered in .22 Long Rifle and .38 Special chamberings. Manufactured with fine carbon steel, it was available in both blued and nickel plated finishes. Early blued Troopers boasted a two-tone color scheme with dull Colt Royal Blue on the flat surfaces and a black bead blasted texture on the edges and cylinder flutes. Both Target and Service versions of the Trooper were available, the Target models sporting hand-filling Walnut grips, larger and wider target hammers, and adjustable iron sights. Service versions featured smaller more basic hammers and stocks, and fixed sights. Barrel lengths available included four inch in .22 caliber and four and six inch in .38 Special; the .22 was intended as a ‘practice’ weapon. All the Troopers from this series had hammer mounted firing pins. The Trooper was targeted at the entry-level and Law enforcement service-level segment of the firearms market while the highly polished and expensive 357 model revolver was intended to be their premium offering. Both models shared the same forged and labor intensive hand-fitted internal lockwork, however.[1]

After the introduction of the more expensive Python in 1955, most purchasers bypassed the .357 model, in favor the Python for a top-end revolver or the Trooper for a more basic one. This development motivated Colt to discontinue the basic .38 Special Trooper in 1961, and to do away with the .357 moniker, so they renamed it Trooper. The new offering retained the .357 magnum chambering and frame-mounted firing pin, but kept the entry-level revolver’s more subdued finish. The Trooper continued to be offered in .22 Long rifle, and like all .357 Magnums, offered the capability of firing .38 Special ammunition as well.[1]

Insured shipping to FFL where allowed--$30
